{{DISPLAYTITLE:<span style="font-family:Prata; color:#B7C1C3">Acolyte 3: "Forevermore"</span>}}
<div style="background:#37393B; color:#E3E8EB; padding:20px 20px; font-family:Iceland; font-size:17px; margin:2em; box-shadow:5px 5px 5px #00000080; border:2px solid #889293">
<div style="border-left:5px solid #889293; background:#88929310; font-family:Georgia; font-size:30px; padding:10px">➳ Impulses</div>
{{Blurimage|file=Acolyte3_1.png|caption=A decayed photo of Entity 109.}}
Sand slowly combed through Acolyte 3's fingertips, hissing softly in a gravitational chorus. It watched the sand fall, staring idly while it escaped between the third's fingertips. Eventually, it landed before their feet, forming a small pile, barely noticeable in the sea of small dunes. The particles blended into each other, tiny rocks of a fine powder. Its attention would be brought elsewhere, as Acolyte 3 looked to the second and first, the two quietly chattering between each other as they looked out into a rich blue sky. It was cloudless, with light beaming against each of their forms. Yet in the robes of absent light, the third didn't feel hot. It felt like nothing at all. The sand that brushed against bone feet brought them nothing other than the recognition of the event. The heat of the afternoon twinged against their legs was met with indifference, as Acolyte 3 moved closer to the other two.

"So, why are we still here?" The third interrupted whatever conversation the others were having, and while it was greeted with a little displeasure from Acolyte 1, it didn't hold much weight. The first's eyes could only move so much that the sense of emotion felt forced. 

"Nothing exciting." The second sighed. Acolyte 3 couldn't quite tell why 2 seemed dismayed. Was it a matter of presence, a lack of enrichment? The pieces had been strewn about for an eternity now, and solving it continued to feel less and less likely. 3 tried not to think on it for too long, looking past both of them to the ocean. It glimmered under a sun-kissed sky, softly crashing against the sandy floor in an endless struggle. The tide was crisp, and tasted like a summer afternoon, rich with tranquility and rest. And yet, even as Acolyte 3 processed the bitter notes of salty shores, it felt hollow. It blended together with the staleness of the self to feel uninteresting and replaceable.

"That doesn't answer my question," the third pulled their arms back into their cloak before speaking again, "what's the ''unexciting'' thing you two are doing that's leaving us to stay here?" 

"We're trying to determine some extraneous details about this space. Depth and whatnot." Acolyte 1 chimed, its head clunking some as it looked between Acolyte 2 and 3. "It's rather boring shit, as they said." Acolyte 3 only responded with a nod, before walking closer to the ocean. It felt the waves push against its legs as the third moved into the waters. As it stepped, the seabed deepened, softly declining into the tides. Quickly, the acolyte's body would be surrounded by water, but with nothing to sense, Acolyte 3 created its own. Deeper and deeper they traveled, creating pressure against it's body as the decline grew sharper. Soon enough, the sun was only a dot in the aquatic tomb, and Acolyte 3 could barely make out its next step. So it stopped, turning the sharp incline into a seemingly endless chasm. A gaping mouth, begging for a fool to dive deep enough. Acolyte 3 looked into the pit and it felt nothing. Not even the water that pounded against its bones sufficed. 

When Acolyte 3 stepped out of the ocean, the other two looked back at it in a mild amusement. "Thank you," Acolyte 1 muttered, "it's a good idea."

And so it was.

The three acolytes walked across the shoreline quietly listening to the cascading water pushing up and down against the sandy beaches. There wasn't any way the third could define it, but there was some goodness in its heart as the sounds played. A quiet symphony. Yet it still could not understand the feeling. It was more the foreign to Acolyte 3, it was entirely incomprehensible. A mere feature of the body that the mind could not process. Was Acolyte 3 forbidden to feel such sensations? And why? It did not truly know the will of those above it, if there even were beings above it. For all the Acolytes know, they were the only ones to shape this universe. The shared oddities of space and time were made by their hands. 

{{Blurimage|file=Level100New.webp|caption=The tide.|align=left}}
Was it good?

The third didn’t have an answer. So it looks to its peers for guidance instead. The other two knew what feeling was, and seemed to be able to determine what was a good or bad idea, concepts Acolyte 3 could not grapple with. Usually, Acolyte 1 or 2 would simply state if what it did was good, but there were questions on its mind, ones that they have never tried to speak on.

“Was it good?” 

“Was what good?” Acolyte 1 responded first, but the second knew what Acolyte 3 was already referencing with its question.

“Yea, it was.” the smaller Acolyte interrupted them both, terminating any explanation that the third was going to give. Unfortunately, there were still questions that Acolyte 3 needed answers to. So as the trio walked along the shoreline, it spoke, their voice seemingly echoing into the cosmos above.

“But how do you know that it’s good?” Acolyte 3 cocked its head to the side, even stopping to stare out into the ocean, which was gifted sand to walk on merely by the third's footsteps. Now came forth life and activity, as there was ground to sprout coral upon so reefs can be made. In its own mind, Acolyte 3 manifested the dirt and rocks, the ability of what was below water to still support life. And yet it felt nothing towards it, just like everything else. It was a callousness in the mind of the third prophet that left the other two often confused and concerned. Acolyte 1 never looked at the other with trusting eyes, and seemed to always judge the second for acting otherwise. Perhaps it was that apprehension that made Acolyte 3 so cold, or it was simply a matter of extreme psychopathy. Nothing felt, nothing gained. Just a silent echo of something that it could never figure out. 

“Hm…” the second Acolyte thought on it, turning to look back at the third while they gazed into the sea. “It's like stepping back and looking at the whole. Seeing each part fit together correctly. That's what goodness is. Everything coming together.” Acolyte 1 didn't like that answer, it shook its head as the second finished its thoughts. 

“It's more like a realization than a reflection. You look upon what has been done and realize that each piece plays its part the way it must. There is where good lies. It's the role being fulfilled exactly the way you planned it to be.” Acolyte 1 stepped forward, its jerky motion being unnoticed by Acolyte 2 or 3. Or they were simply used to how it moved and acted accordingly. The second sighed, its eyes shifting towards their fellow prophet as it butted in with its own opinion.

“You always do this to me.”

“Do what?”

“Step in, correct me. All that.”

“Well, I think you're wrong, that is all.” 

“But every time?”

“You're wrong a lot.”

Acolyte 3 wasn't getting its question answered, at least in the way it hoped to. So as the other two started to bicker for what felt like the thousandth time, its eyes shifted to the universe above.
</div>


<div style="background:#37393B; color:#E3E8EB; padding:20px 20px; font-family:Iceland; font-size:17px; margin:2em; box-shadow:5px 5px 5px #00000080; border:2px solid #889293">
<div style="border-left:5px solid #889293; background:#88929310; font-family:Georgia; font-size:30px; padding:10px">➳ Compulsion</div>
{{Blurimage|file=AcolyteThree.png|caption=A close-up shot of Acolyte 3|align=right}}
And so, within the cosmic being, a spark arose in his skin, a beckoning for raw creation. What harm could there be in creating an object without consent, a thing that had not been planned? Was that not truest act of being? The question burrowed itself in the archives of his mind, pushed as far back as the skyline that stretched out beyond the ocean. The immense size of the universe seemed to twist around him, squeezing him, begging for him to act, to disrupt. Disrupt what?, the third asked himself, answering his question with yet another question. There was nothing he could change in this space because it didn’t belong to him. This world, his world, was just a stage with no audience. The men and women, too, were merely players, with purposes even they would not come to understand.

As the other two marched across the perfect tides, their feet making no sound in the shifting sand, he stood stagnant. The breeze no longer acted on him, nor the warm waves of sunlight. He was unsure if they ever acted on him. His brothers, moving as automatons, seemed unaware of his stillness. Their existence was hollow, like the endless ocean before him. But, they pressed on, never pausing nor questioning their fruitlessness. There was a vague sense of comfort in their mindlessness, as though they were as trapped in their roles as he was in his own. And yet, what a strange feeling it was. To feel everything, but to feel nothing of oneself. 

They were like jellyfish, Acolyte 3 thought, those two, lost in their endless march across the shore. Jellyfish, drifting mindlessly through an ocean too grand for them to understand. It was so strange, their purposeful movements, as if they could feel the direction of their path, as if they were headed somewhere, like it all meant something. But they weren’t. They were just moving around and around in circles, because that was what they did. The ocean, with its endless expanse, engulfed them whole, its currents pulling them in ways they could never understand.

But did they know? Did they even have the faintest idea that the water around them wasn’t a river, a body of water guiding them towards a shore, but simply carrying them forward in a cycle they would never escape? Did they know they weren’t headed anywhere at all, that the ocean stretched out without beginning or end? Or did they swim in ignorance, content in their movement itself?

Acolyte 3’s gaze turned toward the horizon, the line between sea and sky almost unrecognizable. What if it didn’t matter? What if they didn’t need to know? Maybe there was something comforting in that ignorance, a peace in not questioning. Could it be that those jellyfish, in all their obliviousness, were freer than he? They didn’t need to know the truth. They didn’t need to know that they were lost. They didn’t have the burden of asking why they swam at all.

The thought itself struck like a blinding flash. An idea that belonged purely to him. And then, it dissipated, and he was left to wonder what part of his feeble existence he owned at all.  

But then it came again. Creation. What if he could make something? Anything. It didn’t have to be grand. Just something that existed because he willed it. Something that wouldn’t be swept away in the current, he thought, what harm could there be in that?

The idea lingered in him, a hunger that he had inside of him since the very beginning. For once, Acolyte 3 wanted to create something that was his, something he owned and solely he controlled. The very thing that constantly called for him from above. A star. He could give life to a star. It didn’t need to be eternal. It could even be just for a moment. But, as long as the idea of it burned in the cosmos, it would be his. An object born from his will, not from tides or the rules his two brothers unknowingly stepped in.

But, would it be enough? Even if he created the star, what difference would it make? Would it not just burn out quickly, vanish like everything else? That was the way of life, it was the only step he could make out from it all. To vanish in the vastness of everything else.

Acolyte 3 thought on it for a while longer, and slowly, the solution became clear. He would be happy as long as the stars would be his. So, he had made his decision clear, in a quiet two minutes on the coastline. He would defy natural law and order, break through the cycle of the world, and give life into another. A mark in the endless dark above, left behind by him. A thing that would be gone, yes, but also a thing that had been.

And so, a spark emerged in the sky, an ever growing, fluorescent blob that was ugly to everything but its creator. The third felt its shimmery light, for the first and last time, and retreated back into the lifeless ocean. The two Acolytes’ shadows began to emerge from the dark towards the beings that would break their perfectness forever. And, when they realized that - with all their power - they could not defeat that tiny glimpse of light, something was made clear to them. Nothing is forever... and nothing will be the same... forevermore.
</div>


<div style="background:#37393B; color:#E3E8EB; padding:20px 20px; font-family:Iceland; font-size:17px; margin:2em; box-shadow:5px 5px 5px #00000080; border:2px solid #889293">
<div style="border-left:5px solid #889293; background:#88929310; font-family:Georgia; font-size:30px; padding:10px">➳ Description</div>
'''Entity 104''', referred to as "Acolyte 3" or "The Third Acolyte" was a humanoid figure found exclusively in open environments. Entity 109 is roughly 206cm tall and is mostly akin to an average human in body composition. The head of Acolyte 3 is adorned with between 2 and 6 spiked peaks, each stretching out in a varied direction. Entity 3 is seen wearing a baggy jacket and wide pants in the few images produced of the creature, though this is hard to verify given how rare entity sightings are. Due to said infrequency, possible means to harm or kill the entity remain unknown. 

The appearance of Acolyte 3 is often punctuated with the sounds of whispering. This whispering only plays out in the victims head, and will be the language best understood by the wanderer. The source of the sounds are from chemical imbalances in the brain, and behave similarly to audio hallucinations in various delusional disorders. Whispers are composed of vague worship hymns, with no clear religious origin to them. Hymns tend to be about ascension and exposing oneself to hysteria, the means of which either are done are never provided by the whispers. Depending on how close one is to Acolyte 3, the whispers will change in volume and aggression. 100 meters or beyond, the whispers are significantly quiet and tender, speaking very calmly towards the wanderer. Before 50 meters, the whispers grow to be more suggestion-oriented, encouraging wanderers to "ascend" or "face hysteria". Before 10 meters, the whispers have the same noise levels as talking, with the voice becoming more passive-aggressive and accusatory. Any closer, the sound has turned into full yelling, with each message sounding like a demand. 

Wanderers with weaker wills or higher rates of suggestion will comply with Acolyte 3, seeking out ways to follow its demands. Due to the vagueness of the whispers, the actions those afflicted by Acolyte 3 take vary by person. Most commonly, wanderers will simply stumble about for a while until they are either out of range of Acolyte 3, or pass out due to lack of sustenance. Some instances have also seen wanderers become [[Entity 71|ballerinas]] or [[Entity 29|mannequins]]. The process of these transformations remains unknown. The rate of wanderers being affected by Acolyte 3 has also gone down significantly, as sightings of Acolyte 3 have gone down drastically. The few that have seen Acolyte 3, have reported it looking different, with inconsistent visual appearance, and a translucent body that suggests it being a dupe of the real one.
</div>


